<subSubSection id="C3486534FF0FFF6CFF756991FBF8FDF7" lastPageId="233" lastPageNumber="226" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8BED36BFFF0FFF6DFF756991FBAAFA40" blockId="232.[151,1128,939,1571]" pageId="232" pageNumber="229">
The 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0FFF6DFF236997FE74FC00" authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1944" box="[227,438,941,963]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neglecta">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0FFF6DFF236997FE74FC00" box="[227,438,941,963]" italics="true" pageId="232" pageNumber="229">Anthomyza neglecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group was established by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC34B4EFF0FFF6DFD036991FCB0FC00" author="ROHACEK J." box="[707,882,939,963]" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" pagination="1 - 328" refId="ref334646" refString="ROHACEK J. 2006 a: A monograph of Palaearctic Anthomyzidae (Diptera) Part 1. Casopis Slezskeho Zemskeho Muzea, Opava (A) 55 (supplement 1): 1 - 328." type="journal article" year="2006">ROHÁĆEK (2006a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC34B4EFF0FFF6DFCBA6991FC7EFC00" author="ROHACEK J." box="[890,956,939,963]" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" pagination="1 - 180" refId="ref334979" refString="ROHACEK J. 2009 a: A monograph of Palaearctic Anthomyzidae (Diptera) Part 2. Casopis Slezskeho Zemskeho Muzea, Opava (A) 58 (supplement 1): 1 - 180." type="journal article" year="2009">2009a</bibRefCitation>
) for three Palaearctic species, viz. 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0FFF6DFE9D69F7FDA2FC20" authority="Collin, 1944" authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1944" box="[349,608,971,995]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neglecta">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0FFF6DFE9D69F7FE16FC20" box="[349,468,973,995]" italics="true" pageId="232" pageNumber="229">A. neglecta</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFC34B4EFF0FFF6DFE1969F1FDA2FC20" author="COLLIN J. E." box="[473,608,971,995]" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" pagination="265 - 272" refId="ref324323" refString="COLLIN J. E. 1944: The British species of Anthomyzidae (Diptera). Entomologist's Monthly Magazine 80: 265 - 272." type="journal article" year="1944">Collin, 1944</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0FFF6DFDA969F7FC5DFC20" authority="Elberg, 1968" authorityName="Elberg" authorityYear="1968" box="[617,927,971,995]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paraneglecta">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0FFF6DFDA969F7FCD1FC20" box="[617,787,973,995]" italics="true" pageId="232" pageNumber="229">A. paraneglecta</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFC34B4EFF0FFF6DFCD869F1FC5DFC20" author="ELBERG K. &amp; JU" box="[792,927,971,995]" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" pagination="629 - 632" refId="ref325444" refString="ELBERG K. JU. 1968: Novye dannye po faune dvukrylykh sem. Anthomyzidae (Diptera) Pribaltiki. (New data on the fauna of Anthomyzidae (Diptera) from Baltic area). Entomologicheskoe Obozrenie 47: 629 - 632 (in Russian with English summary)." type="journal article" year="1968">Elberg, 1968</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0FFF6DFC1169F7FEF8FBC0" authority="Rohacek, 2006" authorityName="Rohacek" authorityYear="2006" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orineglecta">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0FFF6DFC1169F7FBA4FC20" box="[977,1126,973,995]" italics="true" pageId="232" pageNumber="229">A. orineglecta</emphasis>
Roháček, 2006
</taxonomicName>
. In the Nearctic Region, four additional species belonging to this group have been found, including 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0FFF6DFE4A6E37FCC4FBE0" authority="(Loew, 1863)" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Loew" baseAuthorityYear="1863" box="[394,774,1035,1059]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegata">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0FFF6DFE4A6E37FDACFBE0" box="[394,622,1037,1059]" italics="true" pageId="232" pageNumber="229">Anthomyza variegata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC34B4EFF0FFF6DFDBD6E31FD3CFBE0" author="LOEW H." box="[637,766,1035,1059]" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" pagination="275 - 326" refId="ref328368" refString="LOEW H. 1863: Diptera Americae septentrionalis indigena. Centuria quarta. Berliner Entomologische Zeitschrift 7: 275 - 326." type="journal article" year="1863">Loew, 1863</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and three new species described below, viz. 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0FFF6DFED56E17FE44FB80" authority="Roháćek &amp; Barber, 2016" authorityName="Roháćek &amp; Barber" authorityYear="2016" box="[277,390,1069,1091]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dichroa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0FFF6DFED56E17FE44FB80" box="[277,390,1069,1091]" italics="true" pageId="232" pageNumber="229">A. dichroa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A21557D6FF0FFF6DFE4E6E11FE26FB81" box="[398,484,1067,1090]" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0FFF6DFE306E17FDABFB80" authority="Roháćek &amp; Barber, 2016" authorityName="Roháćek &amp; Barber" authorityYear="2016" box="[496,617,1069,1091]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gibbiger" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0FFF6DFE306E17FDABFB80" box="[496,617,1069,1091]" italics="true" pageId="232" pageNumber="229">A. gibbiger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A21557D6FF0FFF6DFDB16E11FD04FB81" box="[625,710,1067,1090]" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0FFF6DFD3C6E17FC5EFB80" authority="Roháćek &amp; Barber, 2016" authorityName="Roháćek &amp; Barber" authorityYear="2016" box="[764,924,1069,1091]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orthogibbus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0FFF6DFD3C6E17FC5EFB80" box="[764,924,1069,1091]" italics="true" pageId="232" pageNumber="229">A. orthogibbus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A21557D6FF0FFF6DFC646E11FC3AFB81" box="[932,1016,1067,1090]" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
However, although all the above-named species are distinctly related, the inclusion of the Nearctic species required redennition of the taxonomic limits of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0FFF6DFCDA6E57FC51FB40" authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1944" box="[794,915,1133,1155]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neglecta">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0FFF6DFCDA6E57FC51FB40" box="[794,915,1133,1155]" italics="true" pageId="232" pageNumber="229">A. neglecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, because not all added species share all characters used by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC34B4EFF0FFF6DFD416EB1FCB0FB60" author="ROHACEK J." box="[641,882,1163,1187]" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" pagination="1 - 328" refId="ref334646" refString="ROHACEK J. 2006 a: A monograph of Palaearctic Anthomyzidae (Diptera) Part 1. Casopis Slezskeho Zemskeho Muzea, Opava (A) 55 (supplement 1): 1 - 328." type="journal article" year="2006">ROHÁĆEK (2006a: 129)</bibRefCitation>
to diagnose the group. The expanded 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0FFF6DFEF56E97FE6FFB00" authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1944" box="[309,429,1197,1219]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neglecta">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0FFF6DFEF56E97FE6FFB00" box="[309,429,1197,1219]" italics="true" pageId="232" pageNumber="229">A. neglecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group can be best diagnosed by the following (most of them obviously apomorphic) characters: (1) white pilosity of the 1st antennal nagellomere long; (2) pregonite simplined and with a very reduced posterior process; (3) postgonite usually with 1 lateral seta; (4) saccus of distiphallus shortened; (5) nlum robust, not attenuated apically but ending in a curved digitiform terminal process; (6) female T7+S7 forming a compact conical sclerite with anterolateroventral (often pouch-like) lobes; (7) annular sclerite in female genital chamber small and asymmetrically bent; (8) spermathecae with shallow terminal impression.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BED36BFFF0FFF6CFF756FB1FC09FEF7" blockId="232.[151,1128,939,1571]" lastBlockId="233.[113,1090,220,820]" lastPageId="233" lastPageNumber="226" pageId="232" pageNumber="229">
The 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0FFF6DFF256FB7FE99FA60" authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1944" box="[229,347,1421,1443]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neglecta">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0FFF6DFF256FB7FE99FA60" box="[229,347,1421,1443]" italics="true" pageId="232" pageNumber="229">A. neglecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group was also connrmed as monophyletic (although with only European species included) by analyses of molecular data (ROHÁĆEK et al. 2009; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC34B4EFF0FFF6DFC466F91FF13FA20" author="ROHACEK J. &amp; TOTHOVA A." pageId="232" pageNumber="229" pagination="165 - 176" refId="ref336515" refString="ROHACEK J. &amp; TOTHOVA A. 2014: Morphology versus DNA - what will bring clarity to the relationships of phylogenetically unclear genera of Anthomyzidae (Diptera)? Arthropod Systematics &amp; Phylogeny 72: 165 - 176." type="journal article" year="2014">ROHÁĆEK &amp; TÓTHOVÁ 2014</bibRefCitation>
). Its relationship to other groups of 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0FFF6DFD8B6FF7FD00FA20" authorityName="Fallen" authorityYear="1810" box="[587,706,1485,1507]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0FFF6DFD8B6FF7FD00FA20" box="[587,706,1485,1507]" italics="true" pageId="232" pageNumber="229">Anthomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has not been recognized with certainty. Two separate analyses of morphological (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC34B4EFF0FFF6DFDA66FD1FCD5F9C0" author="ROHACEK J." box="[614,791,1515,1539]" pageId="232" pageNumber="229" pagination="1 - 180" refId="ref334979" refString="ROHACEK J. 2009 a: A monograph of Palaearctic Anthomyzidae (Diptera) Part 2. Casopis Slezskeho Zemskeho Muzea, Opava (A) 58 (supplement 1): 1 - 180." type="journal article" year="2009">ROHÁĆEK 2009a</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="13692A3AFF0FFF6DFCE46FD1FC40F9C0" box="[804,898,1515,1539]" captionStart="Figs 139–145" captionStartId="92.[151,188,1458,1477]" captionTargetBox="[177,1099,412,1406]" captionTargetId="figure-54@92.[151,1126,388,1440]" captionTargetPageId="92" captionText="Figs 139–145. Arganthomyza bivittata Roháček &amp; Barber, 2013, paratype female (Canada: Ontario). 139 – female genital chamber and apex of postabdomen, laterally; 140 – spermatheca; 141, 142 – ventral receptacle, whole laterally (141) and apex ventrally (142); 143 – spermatheca; 144 – internal sclerites, laterally; 145 – the same, ventrally. Scales = 0.1 mm (Fig. 139) and 0.05 mm (others). For abbreviations see p. 11. Adapted from ROHÁĆEK &amp; BARBER (2013: Figs 93–99)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272899" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272899/files/figure.png" pageId="232" pageNumber="229">Fig. 141</figureCitation>
) and molecular data (ROHÁĆEK et al. 2009: 
<figureCitation id="13692A3AFF0FFF6DFE466C31FE07F9E0" box="[390,453,1547,1571]" captionStart="Figs 2–3" captionStartId="10.[151,187,1534,1553]" captionTargetBox="[168,1110,219,1518]" captionTargetId="figure-11@10.[168,1111,219,1518]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 2–3. Nearctic species of the genus Anthomyza. 2 – A. shewelli sp. nov., a pair (male on left) on leaf of Carex sp. (Canada:Ontario:Dubreuilville, Magpie River), body length ca.2.4 mm (male) and 3.1 mm (female); 3 –A.mcalpinei sp. nov., living male, laterally (Canada:Ontario:Sault Ste. Marie, Finn Hill), body length ca.2.8 mm. Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272833" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272833/files/figure.png" pageId="232" pageNumber="229">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) placed it as a sister group to an E. Palaearctic clade including 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFFB16AE4FDF4FF37" authority="Sueyoshi &amp; Rohacek, 2003" authorityName="Sueyoshi &amp; Rohacek" authorityYear="2003" box="[113,566,220,244]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ssavosterna">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFFB16AE4FEC5FF37" box="[113,263,220,244]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. ssavosterna</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFC34B4EFF0EFF6CFECF6AE6FDF4FF37" author="SUEYOSHI M. &amp; ROHACEK J." box="[271,566,220,244]" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" pagination="17 - 36" refId="ref338460" refString="SUEYOSHI M. &amp; ROHACEK J. 2003: Anthomyzidae (Diptera: Acalyptrata) from Japan and adjacent areas. Entomological Science 6: 17 - 36." type="journal article" year="2003">Sueyoshi &amp; Roháček, 2003</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and the sister pair 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFCC76AE4FBEBFF37" authority="Rohacek, 1984" authorityName="Rohacek" authorityYear="1984" box="[775,1065,220,244]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellatrix">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFCC76AE4FC42FF37" box="[775,896,222,244]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. bellatrix</emphasis>
Roháček, 1984
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFFB16AC4FDCAFED7" authority="Sueyoshi &amp; Rohacek, 2003" authorityName="Sueyoshi &amp; Rohacek" authorityYear="2003" box="[113,520,252,276]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trifurca">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFFB16AC4FF1DFED7" box="[113,223,254,276]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. trifurca</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFC34B4EFF0EFF6CFF246AC6FDCAFED7" author="SUEYOSHI M. &amp; ROHACEK J." box="[228,520,252,276]" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" pagination="17 - 36" refId="ref338460" refString="SUEYOSHI M. &amp; ROHACEK J. 2003: Anthomyzidae (Diptera: Acalyptrata) from Japan and adjacent areas. Entomological Science 6: 17 - 36." type="journal article" year="2003">Sueyoshi &amp; Roháček, 2003</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, while the molecular analysis of 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC34B4EFF0EFF6CFCA26AC6FF76FEF7" author="ROHACEK J. &amp; TOTHOVA A." pageId="233" pageNumber="226" pagination="165 - 176" refId="ref336515" refString="ROHACEK J. &amp; TOTHOVA A. 2014: Morphology versus DNA - what will bring clarity to the relationships of phylogenetically unclear genera of Anthomyzidae (Diptera)? Arthropod Systematics &amp; Phylogeny 72: 165 - 176." type="journal article" year="2014">ROHÁĆEK &amp; TÓTHOVÁ (2014</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="13692A3AFF0EFF6CFF7E6B26FF38FEF7" box="[190,250,284,308]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[113,144,1535,1554]" captionTargetBox="[132,1088,177,1483]" captionTargetId="figure-14@7.[113,1088,157,1508]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 1. Anthomyza dichroa sp. nov., male, general habitus (Canada: Ontario: Sault Ste. Marie, Bristol Place Park), body length ca. 2.5 mm. Based on photograph by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272831" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272831/files/figure.png" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) postulated it to have a common ancestor with the 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFCDD6B24FCBCFEF7" authorityName="Andersson" authorityYear="1976" box="[797,894,286,308]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="collini">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFCDD6B24FCBCFEF7" box="[797,894,286,308]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. collini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BED36BFFF0EFF6CFF506B06FBF8FDF7" blockId="233.[113,1090,220,820]" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">
Inasmuch as three of the Nearctic species (
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFD916B04FD11FE97" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Loew" baseAuthorityYear="1863" box="[593,723,318,340]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegata">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFD916B04FD11FE97" box="[593,723,318,340]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. variegata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFD1F6B04FC94FE97" authorityName="Roháćek &amp; Barber" authorityYear="2016" box="[735,854,318,340]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gibbiger">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFD1F6B04FC94FE97" box="[735,854,318,340]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. gibbiger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFCA26B04FBC2FE97" authorityName="Roháćek &amp; Barber" authorityYear="2016" box="[866,1024,318,340]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orthogibbus">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFCA26B04FBC2FE97" box="[866,1024,318,340]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. orthogibbus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) have relatively simple, nat and not or weakly medially bent gonostyli (plesiomorphic, those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFBEA6B64FF15FE57" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Loew" baseAuthorityYear="1863" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegata">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFBEA6B64FF15FE57" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. variegata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of the most ancestral 
<typeStatus id="54E9881DFF0EFF6CFE056B46FE35FE57" box="[453,503,380,404]" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">type</typeStatus>
), it is possible that all Palaearctic species (
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFC016B44FBFBFE57" authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1944" box="[961,1081,382,404]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neglecta">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFC016B44FBFBFE57" box="[961,1081,382,404]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. neglecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFFB16BA4FEDDFE77" authorityName="Elberg" authorityYear="1968" box="[113,287,414,436]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paraneglecta">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFFB16BA4FEDDFE77" box="[113,287,414,436]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. paraneglecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFEF06BA4FE09FE77" authorityName="Rohacek" authorityYear="2006" box="[304,459,414,436]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orineglecta">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFEF06BA4FE09FE77" box="[304,459,414,436]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. orineglecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) which have strongly curved gonostyli could be derived later and probably from the ancestor of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFD8B6B84FD12FE17" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Loew" baseAuthorityYear="1863" box="[587,720,446,468]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegata">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFD8B6B84FD12FE17" box="[587,720,446,468]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. variegata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFD2F6B84FCA2FE17" authorityName="Roháćek &amp; Barber" authorityYear="2016" box="[751,864,446,468]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dichroa">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFD2F6B84FCA2FE17" box="[751,864,446,468]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. dichroa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sister pair (probable synapomorphies: very long ciliation of 1st nagellomere; 1 pair of internal sclerites in female genital chamber). They (together with 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFDCD6BC4FD53FDD7" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Loew" baseAuthorityYear="1863" box="[525,657,510,532]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegata">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFDCD6BC4FD53FDD7" box="[525,657,510,532]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. variegata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFD056BC4FCF7FDD7" authorityName="Roháćek &amp; Barber" authorityYear="2016" box="[709,821,510,532]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dichroa">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFD056BC4FCF7FDD7" box="[709,821,510,532]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. dichroa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) also lack the distinctive synapomorphies of the other Nearctic sister pair (
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFD416824FD3BFDF7" authorityName="Roháćek &amp; Barber" authorityYear="2016" box="[641,761,542,564]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gibbiger">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFD416824FD3BFDF7" box="[641,761,542,564]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. gibbiger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFCD56824FC76FDF7" authorityName="Roháćek &amp; Barber" authorityYear="2016" box="[789,948,542,564]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orthogibbus">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFCD56824FC76FDF7" box="[789,948,542,564]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. orthogibbus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), see below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3486534FF0EFF6CFF506806FD2DFCF7" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BED36BFFF0EFF6CFF506806FD2DFCF7" blockId="233.[113,1090,220,820]" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">
Another hypothesis (preferred here) presupposes that all four Nearctic species are derived from a common ancestor (possible synapomorphies: aedeagal part of folding apparatus with armature reduced to small tubercles; female T7+S7 dorsomedially shortened and weakened to interrupted; internal sclerites of female genital chamber weakly sclerotized) so forming the sister group to a branch with Palaearctic species (
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFDAC6884FD22FD17" authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1944" box="[620,736,702,724]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neglecta">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFDAC6884FD22FD17" box="[620,736,702,724]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. neglecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFD2C6884FC50FD17" authorityName="Elberg" authorityYear="1968" box="[748,914,702,724]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paraneglecta">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFD2C6884FC50FD17" box="[748,914,702,724]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. paraneglecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF0EFF6CFC5E6884FBF3FD17" authorityName="Rohacek" authorityYear="2006" box="[926,1073,702,724]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="233" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orineglecta">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF0EFF6CFC5E6884FBF3FD17" box="[926,1073,702,724]" italics="true" pageId="233" pageNumber="226">A. orineglecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The latter three species can be clustered on the basis of the following synapomorphies: caudal process of transandrium with spinulae reduced and female genital chamber with annular sclerite situated ventrally under the paired internal sclerites.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
